NOTES_1THESSALONIANS = {
    1: {
        1: 'GREEK: "Ekklēsia" (ἐκκλησία, Strong\'s G1577) denotes a called-out assembly, not a building; its LXX background translates Hebrew "qahal," the congregation of Israel. The phrase "in God the Father and the Lord Jesus Christ" is remarkable, placing Father and Son in a single prepositional phrase as the sphere in which the assembly exists — a striking co-ordination of divine persons. HISTORICAL: Thessalonica was the capital of the Roman province of Macedonia, a major port city on the Via Egnatia. This letter is widely regarded as the earliest Pauline epistle, written c. AD 49–51 from Corinth.',
        3: 'THEOLOGICAL: The triad "work of faith, labor of love, endurance of hope" maps onto the great Pauline virtues of faith, love, and hope (1 Cor 13:13). Each virtue is linked to active expression — faith produces work (ergon), love produces toilsome labor (kopos), and hope produces steadfast endurance (hypomonē). GREEK: "Hypomonē" (ὑπομονή, G5281) denotes not passive waiting but active, resolute endurance under pressure. The phrase "before our God and Father" (emprosthen tou theou) evokes divine-court language — their lives are lived in the presence of the divine tribunal.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Eklogē" (ἐκλογή, G1589) — election, choosing out — is here grounded not in human merit but in divine love: "beloved by God." Paul\'s confidence in their election is confirmed by the evidence of the Spirit\'s power (v. 5). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The concept of God\'s election of a people echoes the Deuteronomy 32:8–9 worldview where YHWH chose Israel as his own portion from among the nations; now this election extends to Gentile believers in Thessalonica.',
        5: 'GREEK: "Plērophoria" (πληροφορία, G4136) means full assurance or complete conviction — a rare term in the NT (cf. Col 2:2; Heb 6:11; 10:22). THEOLOGICAL: The triadic "power, Holy Spirit, full assurance" describes the gospel\'s arrival not as mere rhetoric (logos monon) but as a divine incursion. This distinguishes apostolic preaching from Greco-Roman sophistic oratory, grounding its efficacy in the Spirit rather than human eloquence.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The Thessalonians\' conversion is described in classic covenantal terms: turning (epistrephō) from idols to the living and true God. This echoes prophetic calls in the OT (cf. Isa 44:9–20; Jer 10:10). GREEK: "Zōnti kai alēthinō" (ζῶντι καὶ ἀληθινῷ) — "living and true" — contrasts the God of Israel with the dead and false gods of the nations. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The language of turning from idols to serve the living God implicitly invokes the Deuteronomy 32 framework in which the nations were given over to lesser elohim (cf. Deut 4:19–20; Ps 96:5 LXX), while Israel\'s God alone is the true and living sovereign.',
        10: 'THEOLOGICAL: This verse encapsulates Pauline eschatology: the awaiting (anamenō, a NT hapax legomenon) of Christ\'s return from heaven, his resurrection as the ground of that hope, and deliverance from coming wrath. GREEK: "Anamenein" (ἀναμένειν, G362) appears only here in the NT — it conveys patient, expectant waiting and underscores the forward-looking posture of early Christian faith. TYPOLOGY: "The one delivering us from the wrath that is coming" (ton rhyomenon) uses a present participle, portraying Jesus as the continually active deliverer — echoing the divine rescuer motif from the Exodus and the Psalms (cf. Ps 18:2 LXX; Dan 6:27 LXX). The "coming wrath" (orgē erchomenē) connects to OT Day-of-the-Lord imagery (Joel 2:31; Zeph 1:15) and anticipates the fuller eschatological teaching in chapters 4–5.',
    },
    2: {
        2: 'GREEK: προπαθόντες (propathontes, from propáschō) means "having suffered beforehand," referring to the events in Philippi (Acts 16:19-24). ἐπαρρησιασάμεθα (eparrēsiasametha, from parrhēsiázomai, Strong\'s G3955) means "we spoke boldly/freely," a term denoting courageous public proclamation despite opposition. The phrase ἐν πολλῷ ἀγῶνι ("in much conflict") uses agōn (G73), an athletic contest term suggesting intense spiritual struggle.',
        4: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul establishes that apostolic authority rests on divine approval (δεδοκιμάσμεθα, dedokimasmetha—"we have been tested and approved," perfect passive). The same verb δοκιμάζω (dokimazō, G1381) is used for God\'s testing of hearts, creating a deliberate parallel: the God who approved us is the God who continually examines (present participle) our hearts. Ministry accountability is ultimately vertical, not horizontal.',
        5: 'GREEK: κολακεία (kolakeía, G2850) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "flattery." It was a term of moral censure in Greco-Roman rhetoric, denoting speech designed to manipulate rather than edify. πρόφασις (próphasis, G4392) means "pretext" or "cloak"—an outward cover hiding the true motive of πλεονεξία (pleonexía, G4124), "greedy desire for more."',
        7: 'GREEK: There is a significant textual variant here: ἤπιοι (ēpioi, "gentle") versus νήπιοι (nēpioi, "infants"). The difference is a single letter (nu). Most critical editions read ἤπιοι. τροφός (trophós, G5162) refers specifically to a nursing mother or wet-nurse, not merely a caretaker. θάλπω (thálpō, G2282) means "to warm, cherish, tenderly care for" (cf. Eph 5:29), conveying intimate nurturing.',
        8: 'GREEK: ὁμειρόμενοι (homeiromenoi) is a rare word, possibly from ὅμειρος, expressing deep affectionate longing. Some connect it to a root meaning "to yearn over." Paul\'s willingness to share not only the gospel but τὰς ἑαυτῶν ψυχάς ("our own souls/lives") demonstrates that authentic gospel ministry is inseparable from self-giving love.',
        12: 'THEOLOGICAL: The triad of pastoral action—παρακαλοῦντες (exhorting), παραμυθούμενοι (encouraging), μαρτυρόμενοι (solemnly charging)—describes comprehensive spiritual fathering. The goal is walking ἀξίως τοῦ θεοῦ ("worthily of God"), who is described as the One presently calling (καλοῦντος, present participle) believers into His own βασιλείαν καὶ δόξαν ("kingdom and glory"), indicating both present and eschatological realities of God\'s reign.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: Paul distinguishes between παραλαβόντες (receiving outwardly, the act of hearing) and ἐδέξασθε (accepting inwardly, welcoming with faith). The word of God is described as ἐνεργεῖται (energeitai, G1754)—"is at work, is operative"—a middle/passive form indicating divine power actively working within believers. This verse is a key text for the doctrine of Scripture\'s divine origin and efficacy (cf. Heb 4:12).',
        14: 'HISTORICAL: συμφυλετῶν (symphyletōn, G4853) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "fellow-countrymen" or "those of the same tribe." The Thessalonian believers suffered persecution from pagan Gentile neighbors, mirroring the Judean churches\' suffering from Jewish opponents. TYPOLOGY: This pattern of the people of God suffering from their own kinsmen echoes the prophetic tradition of Israel persecuting its own prophets (cf. Matt 23:31-37).',
        16: 'THEOLOGICAL: εἰς τὸ ἀναπληρῶσαι αὐτῶν τὰς ἁμαρτίας πάντοτε ("so as to fill up their sins always") echoes Genesis 15:16 where the iniquity of the Amorites must be "filled up." ἔφθασεν (ephthasen, aorist of phthánō, G5348) indicates the wrath "has arrived" or "has overtaken"—a prophetic aorist pointing to divinely determined judgment. εἰς τέλος may mean "unto the end," "completely," or "finally."',
        19: 'GREEK: στέφανος καυχήσεως (stephanos kauchēseōs) is the "crown of boasting"—stephanos (G4735) being the victor\'s wreath, not the royal diadēma. THEOLOGICAL: παρουσία (parousía, G3952) is used here for the coming/arrival of the Lord Jesus—a term used in Hellenistic Greek for the official visit of a king or emperor. Paul identifies the Thessalonians themselves as his eschatological reward at Christ\'s return, binding ecclesiology to eschatology.',
    },
    3: {
        2: 'GREEK: συνεργὸν τοῦ θεοῦ (synergon tou theou, "fellow-worker of God") is a striking title for Timothy, designating him as a co-laborer in divine service. Some manuscripts read διάκονον τοῦ θεοῦ ("servant of God") or συνεργὸν ἡμῶν ("our fellow-worker"), likely scribal softening of the bold original. στηρίξαι (stērixai, Strong\'s G4741) means "to fix firmly, establish"—Paul\'s chief concern is the stabilization of new believers under pressure. παρακαλέσαι (parakalesai, G3870) carries the dual sense of "encourage" and "exhort."',
        3: 'GREEK: σαίνεσθαι (sainesthai, G4525) is a rare word, a NT hapax legomenon. Its basic meaning is "to wag the tail" (of a dog), hence "to fawn upon" or "to beguile," but here in the passive it means "to be shaken, disturbed, moved." THEOLOGICAL: Paul teaches that affliction (θλῖψις, thlipsis) is not incidental but appointed (κείμεθα, keimetha—"we are set, placed, destined"). This echoes the pattern that suffering is integral to the messianic community\'s calling (Acts 14:22; Phil 1:29).',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: ὁ πειράζων (ho peirazōn, "the tempter," G3985) is a title for Satan as the adversary who tests believers to draw them away from faith (Matt 4:3). DIVINE_COUNCIL: The cosmic conflict framework is implicit—the tempter operates as an opposing spiritual agent seeking to render apostolic labor κενός (kenos, "empty, vain"). Paul\'s concern is not merely pastoral but reflects awareness of spiritual warfare against the ecclesia.',
        8: 'GREEK: στήκετε (stēkete, G4739) is a late Greek form meaning "to stand firm, hold one\'s ground," derived from the perfect stem of ἵστημι. It carries a military connotation of maintaining one\'s position. THEOLOGICAL: Paul\'s declaration "now we live" (νῦν ζῶμεν) reveals the depth of apostolic solidarity—his own vitality and spiritual life are bound up with the perseverance of his converts in the Lord.',
        11: 'THEOLOGICAL: The prayer is addressed jointly to "our God and Father himself, and our Lord Jesus," with the singular optative κατευθύναι (kateuthynai, "may he direct") governing both subjects. This grammatical coordination of God the Father and the Lord Jesus under a single verb is a significant indicator of early high Christology, placing Jesus in a position of divine agency alongside the Father. STRUCTURE: Verses 11-13 form a prayer-wish that closes the first half of the epistle, transitioning from narrative to petition.',
        13: 'THEOLOGICAL: παρουσία (parousia, G3952) denotes the "coming, arrival, presence" of the Lord Jesus—a term used in the Hellenistic world for the royal visitation of a king. This is the eschatological anchor of the entire chapter: perseverance in holiness is oriented toward the Lord\'s return. DIVINE_COUNCIL: "With all his holy ones" (μετὰ πάντων τῶν ἁγίων αὐτοῦ) echoes Zechariah 14:5 and Deuteronomy 33:2 (LXX), where God comes with his holy ones—angelic hosts of the divine council. Paul applies this theophanic imagery directly to Jesus, depicting his parousia as a divine-council advent (cf. 2 Thess 1:7; Jude 14).',
    },
    4: {
        3: 'GREEK: "Sanctification" (ἁγιασμός, hagiasmos, Strong\'s G38) denotes the process of being set apart as holy. "Sexual immorality" (πορνεία, porneia, Strong\'s G4202) covers all sexual activity outside the covenant of marriage, a term with broad semantic range in both Jewish and Greco-Roman moral discourse. THEOLOGICAL: Paul grounds ethical behavior not in social convention but in the express will (θέλημα) of God Himself, making holiness a divine imperative rather than a human aspiration.',
        4: 'GREEK: "Vessel" (σκεῦος, skeuos, Strong\'s G4632) is debated—it may refer to one\'s own body (cf. 2 Cor 4:7) or to one\'s wife (cf. 1 Pet 3:7). "Acquire" or "possess" (κτᾶσθαι, ktasthai) suggests ongoing mastery and control. HISTORICAL: In Greco-Roman Thessalonica, sexual license was culturally normative; Paul\'s instruction would have been radically countercultural.',
        6: 'GREEK: "Transgress" (ὑπερβαίνειν, hyperbainein, Strong\'s G5233) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "to go beyond" or "to overstep." "Defraud" (πλεονεκτεῖν, pleonektein) means to take advantage of or exploit. THEOLOGICAL: The Lord (κύριος) is identified as the divine avenger (ἔκδικος), echoing the role of YHWH as judge and vindicator of covenant justice (cf. Deut 32:35; Ps 94:1).',
        8: 'THEOLOGICAL: Rejection of apostolic teaching is equated with rejection of God Himself, establishing the authoritative nature of Spirit-inspired instruction. The present participle "the one giving" (διδόντα, didonta) indicates the ongoing gift of the Holy Spirit, not merely a past event. DIVINE_COUNCIL: God\'s own Spirit (τὸ πνεῦμα αὐτοῦ τὸ ἅγιον) is the agent of sanctification dwelling within believers, marking them as belonging to the divine realm.',
        9: 'GREEK: "Taught by God" (θεοδίδακτοι, theodidaktoi, Strong\'s G2312) is a NT hapax legomenon—a compound of θεός (God) and διδακτός (taught). TYPOLOGY: This echoes the prophetic promise of Isa 54:13 (LXX) and Jer 31:33-34, where God Himself inscribes His instruction upon the hearts of His people in the new covenant era. Jesus cites this tradition in John 6:45.',
        13: 'GREEK: "Those who have fallen asleep" (τῶν κοιμωμένων, tōn koimōmenōn) uses the common early Christian metaphor of death as sleep, implying the expectation of awakening at resurrection. HISTORICAL: The Thessalonian believers were evidently distressed that some among them had died before Christ\'s return. Paul writes to correct a misunderstanding about the fate of deceased believers. THEOLOGICAL: Christian grief is not forbidden but is distinguished from the hopeless grief of those without the resurrection hope (cf. Eph 2:12).',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: The creedal formula "Jesus died and rose again" (ἀπέθανεν καὶ ἀνέστη) forms the ground of eschatological hope: Christ\'s bodily resurrection guarantees the future resurrection of those who belong to Him. The phrase "through Jesus" (διὰ τοῦ Ἰησοῦ) may modify either "fallen asleep" (died in union with Jesus) or "will bring" (God will bring them through Jesus). TYPOLOGY: As the firstfruits of resurrection (1 Cor 15:20), Christ\'s rising prefigures and secures the harvest of all who sleep in Him.',
        16: 'GREEK: "Command" (κέλευσμα, keleusma, Strong\'s G2752) is a NT hapax legomenon denoting a shout of authority, as a military commander or charioteer. "Archangel" (ἀρχαγγέλου, archangelou) appears only here and in Jude 9 in the NT. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The scene depicts a royal descent with heavenly host fanfare—the command, the archangelic voice, and the divine trumpet together signal the arrival of the King with His heavenly court (cf. Exod 19:16; Zech 9:14; Matt 24:31). TYPOLOGY: The trumpet of God echoes Sinai theophany imagery, now fulfilled in Christ\'s Parousia.',
        17: 'GREEK: "Caught up" (ἁρπαγησόμεθα, harpagēsometha, from ἁρπάζω, harpazō, Strong\'s G726) denotes a sudden, forceful seizing—the Latin Vulgate renders this "rapiemur," from which the term "rapture" derives. "Meeting" (ἀπάντησιν, apantēsin, Strong\'s G529) is a technical term in Hellenistic Greek for the civic custom of citizens going out to meet a arriving dignitary and escorting him back into the city. HISTORICAL: The ἀπάντησις imagery suggests not a departure from earth but an escort of the returning King—believers meet the Lord in the air to accompany Him as He descends to reign. THEOLOGICAL: The climactic promise "and so we shall always be with the Lord" (πάντοτε σὺν κυρίῳ ἐσόμεθα) is the ultimate hope—eternal presence with Christ, not a location, is the substance of salvation.',
    },
    5: {
        2: 'GREEK: "Akribōs" (ἀκριβῶς, accurately/exactly) emphasizes the thoroughness of their prior instruction. "Day of the Lord" (ἡμέρα κυρίου) is a direct LXX phrase (cf. Joel 2:1; Amos 5:18; Zeph 1:14) now applied to the return of Christ, identifying Jesus as the Lord of the eschatological day. TYPOLOGY: The "thief in the night" imagery echoes Jesus\' own teaching (Matt 24:43; Luke 12:39) and recurs in 2 Pet 3:10 and Rev 16:15.',
        3: 'GREEK: "Ólethros" (ὄλεθρος, destruction) does not denote annihilation but ruinous loss and judgment (cf. 2 Thess 1:9; 1 Cor 5:5). "Aiphnídios" (αἰφνίδιος, sudden) is rare in the NT, appearing only here and Luke 21:34. TYPOLOGY: The birth-pang (ὠδίν) metaphor draws on OT prophetic imagery for the travail preceding divine intervention (Isa 13:8; Jer 6:24; Mic 4:9-10). The double negative "οὐ μή" with subjunctive expresses the strongest possible negation: escape is utterly impossible.',
        5: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Sons of light" (υἱοὶ φωτός) is a Semitic idiom denoting those who belong to the realm of light; cf. the identical phrase in the Dead Sea Scrolls (1QS III.13—IV.26, "War of the Sons of Light"). Paul shifts from second person ("you are") to first person ("we are not"), uniting himself with the community. DIVINE_COUNCIL: The light/darkness dualism reflects the cosmic conflict between God\'s realm and the dominion of darkness (Col 1:13; Eph 6:12).',
        8: 'TYPOLOGY: The armor imagery draws on Isaiah 59:17 where YHWH himself puts on righteousness as a breastplate and a helmet of salvation—Paul applies the divine warrior\'s own armor to believers. This is developed more fully in Eph 6:13-17. GREEK: "Endysámenoi" (ἐνδυσάμενοι) is an aorist middle participle—"having clothed yourselves"—indicating decisive action. The triad of faith, love, and hope mirrors 1 Thess 1:3.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Étheto" (ἔθετο, from τίθημι) means "appointed" or "destined," indicating God\'s sovereign decree. The contrast is not between wrath and mere rescue but between wrath and "peripoíēsis" (περιποίησιν)—the active obtaining/acquisition of salvation. God\'s purpose for his people is positive possession, not merely escape from judgment. GREEK: "Peripoíēsis" (Strong\'s G4047) can mean both the act of acquiring and the thing acquired (cf. Eph 1:14; 2 Thess 2:14).',
        14: 'GREEK: "Atáktous" (ἀτάκτους, the disorderly) derives from military language for soldiers who break rank (Strong\'s G813); in Thessalonica this likely refers to those who quit working in anticipation of the Lord\'s return (cf. 2 Thess 3:6-11). "Oligopsýchous" (ὀλιγοψύχους, fainthearted/small-souled) is a NT hapax legomenon, though it appears in the LXX (Isa 35:4; 54:6). HISTORICAL: Paul prescribes differentiated pastoral care—not one approach for all, but specific responses matched to specific spiritual conditions.',
        19: 'GREEK: "Sbénnyte" (σβέννυτε) means "quench" or "extinguish," as of a fire (Strong\'s G4570; cf. Matt 12:20; Eph 6:16). The present imperative with "mē" prohibits a continuing action: "stop quenching" or "do not keep quenching." THEOLOGICAL: "To pneûma" (τὸ πνεῦμα) here refers to the Holy Spirit and his active operations within the assembly, closely linked with the next command about prophecy. Suppression of the Spirit\'s gifts was evidently a temptation in the Thessalonian congregation.',
        23: 'GREEK: "Holoteleis" (ὁλοτελεῖς) is a NT hapax legomenon meaning "completely" or "wholly unto the end" (from ὅλος + τέλος). "Holóklēron" (ὁλόκληρον) means "entire, complete in every part," used of unblemished sacrificial animals in the LXX (Deut 27:6). THEOLOGICAL: The tripartite "spirit and soul and body" (πνεῦμα καὶ ψυχὴ καὶ σῶμα) expresses the totality of human existence rather than a strict ontological division. Paul\'s prayer is that the whole person be sanctified and preserved blameless at the "parousia" (παρουσία)—the royal appearing of the Lord Jesus Christ.',
        24: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Pistós" (πιστός, faithful) placed emphatically first declares that the sanctification prayed for in v.23 rests not on human effort but on the character of God who calls. The one calling (ὁ καλῶν, present participle) indicates God\'s ongoing calling activity. "Who also will do it" (ὃς καὶ ποιήσει) is a profound statement of divine faithfulness guaranteeing the completion of salvation (cf. Phil 1:6; Rom 8:30).',
        27: 'GREEK: "Enorkízō" (ἐνορκίζω, I adjure) is a NT hapax legomenon, a strengthened form of "horkízō" (to put under oath). This is the strongest possible charge Paul issues in any of his letters. HISTORICAL: The solemn adjuration that this letter be read to "all the brothers" indicates Paul\'s apostolic authority and suggests the letter functioned as Scripture read aloud in the liturgical assembly. This may also indicate concern that some factions might not hear the letter\'s contents.',
    },
}